Jul 8 2009 	Cute and Clean Hotel... good for couples	My wife and I stayed at the King George for 5 nights July 2-7 while we were sightseeing in San Francisco. Our first impression of the hotel when we walked into the lobby was, &quot;Oh, this is cute!&quot;. The lobby is on the smaller side with the front desk only steps away directly in front of the hotels entrance, with the concerierge to the right. They also have a bar and tea room behind the front desk. Two computers are located next to the front desk, serving as the &quot;business/internet&quot; center. Lobby decor (which is the general decor of the entire hotel) has a British touch, with a large painting of King George on one of the pillars, beautiful draping curtains accenting the large windows, and a simple english printed carpet. Elevator is... well... tiny. You can only fit about 3 people with luggage, and theres only 1 elevator. Most guests just use the stairs, which is narrow, steep, and spirals to the lobby (good exercise after all the eating you plan to do in SF).Our room, as was the observation of most people on this site, was small compared to other hotels we've stayed at. But it served its purpose, a clean and comfortable place to sleep at night. Room was clean and nicely decorated, bed was firm, bathroom was clean. Our room had a queen bed with nightstands and lamps on either side, a comfy cushioined chair, a desk, and an armoire with a TV. Wireless internet is provided free to all guests with a laptop, but if you prefer wired they'll provide you the needed peripherals for a deposit. It was indeed &quot;noisy&quot;, even with the windows closed. But my wife and I fell asleep easily after a whole day of activities. It didn't bother us one bit... in fact, it helped to keep the ambiance that we were staying in the heart of Union Square. Housekeeping was consistent and courteous, they respected our &quot;do not disturb&quot; sign and only cleaned our rooms when we requested. Front desk staff was also very friendly and polite with our requests for amenities. In fact, after just a day, the staff began calling us by our names &quot;Mr. and/or Mrs. ______&quot;. I thought this was very outstanding.The concierge (his name was Sean) helped us in booking 2 tours: Wine Country Tour (through Tower Tours - highly recommended, our driver Joaquin was great!!) and the Alcatraz Island Tour. Sean also provided great suggestions for restaurants and helped with getting a good rate on a car rental (we rented for 3 days to go to Stockton and do some driving on the final 2 days while we were there). Parking is expensive when provided by the hotel $30. There are other cheaper parking garages near by where you can park with in/out privileges... like up Mason Street (ACE Parking for $25).Food/Restaurants: First, I highly recommend Lori's Drive In next door for breakfast. Food and service were exceptional and they have a 1950's theme going on. Humberto was our server for our entire stay when we had breakfast there. Make sure to ask for him and tell him that &quot;Hawaii&quot; recommended him. If you like Indian/Pakistani food, I recommend Chutney's on Jones Street, about two blocks from the hotel. We had a 4 course dinner, with a mango shake for a little over $20. Food was awesome! Seafood can be found everywhere at the Fishermans Wharf. Food hawkers sell crab in the shell, the famous Clam Chowder in a bread bowl, fried seafood fare, and cocktail dishes. I recommend them for snacks or a quick meal. For a nice sit-down meal, I recommend Sabelle and Latorre located near the Fishermans Wharf sign. They have a Chippino that's out of this world! Great food all around SF, you just need to do a some trial and error.Transportation: You really don't need to rent a car. We did only because we had to travel to Stockton (1.5 hours away) to see some friends. But the municipal transportation (Trollies, Cable Cars, Buses) are more than sufficient to get you all round the city. I suggest to buy a MUNI pass from the ticket vendor or from WALGREENS. A 3-day pass is $18.HOTEL was awsome!	
Jul 2 2009 	Good for the money and great location	The King George is in a great location, just minutes away from the BART station, and close to lots of shops, restaurants etc. This does have a downside in that it was a little noisy at night, but then you also wake up to the bustling sounds of the city, and the smell of breakfast cooking, which we loved. We chose it because it was cheaper than many hotels, and it was great for the money. Many reviews mention the small rooms, and yes they are small, but still comfortable. Don't expect a huge room or a huge bathroom, or you will be disappointed. We only stayed for 4 nights as we were moving on, but we had a lovely stay here. It has a great diner next door called &quot;Lori's&quot;.San Francisco in itself is absolutely gorgeous, maybe a little on the pricey side for meals and drinks, but probably given more time we may have searched for better value places. But time was short so just accepted it.Couple of tips, the BART runs from the airport into Union Square which was much cheaper than a taxi, if you can be bothered to get your cases onto the train. Alcatraz was brilliant, and we also did a City coach tour where we saw loads of famous places. Fishermans Wharf is bustling, but well worth a visit, especially the Sea Lions. But as gorgeous as it was, we were glad we were in Union Square as it was a great excuse to jump on a cable car, a brilliant experience, and you see so many more sights. We also loved The Buena Vista, famous for its Irish Coffee, and a scene from &quot;When a Man loves a Woman&quot;. We had a great day cycling, and if you have the energy it is worth it. In one day we cycled over Golden Gate Bridge, to Sausalito which is a gorgeous place to see, from there we cycled towards Muir Woods(although we knew we wouldn't make it up the hills to the woods). Luckily along the way noticed a sign for a shuttle to the woods, it was by chance that we saw this because no-one told us about it. We think the shuttle only runs at weekend but it is worth checking out if you want to see the woods, they are gorgeous! You can lock up your bikes free and jump on the shuttle for a couple of dollars. Once you are back in Sausalito you can get the ferry back with your bike.It is worth doing a little research into the places you want to see before you go, because it is a brilliant place with a great atmosphere!	
