Jan 28 2009 	SF On The Cheap and Cheerful	An old friend and I attended the SF Film Noir Festival and wanted to stay someplace safe, cheap and cheerful. My British neighbor recommended the King George Hotel. The rate we got was $113/night for a King room so we booked two because at that price, we could each have our own. The hotel was perfectly located, exceptionally clean and very quiet despite the usual city noises outside. We got rooms next to each other on the 9th floor (a smoking floor) but there was absolutely no detectable odor of smoke when we entered our rooms nor in the hallways. The beds were nice and firm (which we liked) and the furnishings were in great condition despite their age. The bathrooms were immaculate with modern fixtures and great water pressure. The staff was always helpful and friendly whenever we asked questions or needed food recommendations or tourist info. Our two issues were: (1) the property only has 1 ice machine - and it was on the lobby level at the very rear of the restaurant. It wasn't difficult to get ice but it wasn't very convenient. The other issue was with the concierge - we asked for a recommendation for great chinese restaurant which he provided instantly. Within 5 minutes we were in a cab on the way there. When we arrived at approximately 4:00pm, we were annoyed to find the restaurant did not open for dinner until 5pm. We never did see that particular concierge again - lucky for him. Notwithstanding those 2 issues - we loved the King George, its staff, its charm and its price. Considering how expensive everything else is, this is a exceptional deal for a SF getaway.	
Jan 25 2009 	Right Hotel Wrong Location	The Hotel King George is a beautiful older building, with a pleasant staff and shabby, but clean, rooms. There is no air conditioning in the rooms, so it's necessary to sleep with the windows open, which can be a bit loud.Although the hotel is in the Financial District, it is also right on the edge of the Tenderloin. The Tenderloin is full of panhandlers, and they frequent the sidewalks in front of the Hotel King George. Some days we'd walk out the front door of the hotel to see a panhandler stationed directly under the picturesque green canopy of the King George. It was like walking a gauntlet of beggars, and we were usually hit up for spare change by at least three different people before we could even walk an entire city block. This happened every time we left or returned to the hotel. It's almost as if the citizens of San Francisco look at panhandling as an accepted way to supplement their income.Again, the staff was great. I even noticed one of the maids polishing the brass on the outside of the hotel. This is one of those instances where location, location, location comes into play. Because of the location we will not be staying at the King George again.	
Jan 8 2009 	King George Hotel Has Real San Francisco Charm	I stayed four nights at the King George Hotel for a recent business trip. What a unexpected surprise!As a frequent business traveler, I've grown tired and bored with the major hotels. The rooms are &quot;cookie cutter&quot; mirror images from one city to the next and the service is &quot;luke warm&quot; at best. The King George Hotel offers so much more.Having arrived later in the evening after a delayed flight and a frustrating experience with a taxi driver, I was greeted at the curb by Sean (the Concierge), who discreetly took my baggage inside as I paid the driver (who had not informed me that he did not accept credit cards when I boarded his cab at the airport). Upon entering the hotel, Sean introduced himself, informed me that he would arrange for my transportation back to the airport at the end of my stay with a provider who does take credit cards, flashed a smile, and ended his greeting by saying &quot;welcome home&quot;. Now imagine that happening at a major hotel - never! From that moment on, I was greeted by name by every staff member, all of whom were ready to meet my needs with a smile. The King George Hotel is not a new building. It is a wonderful example of authentic San Francisco architecture that has been well maintained without destroying the original charm. My room, on the top (9th) floor, was a small but very cozy corner room with windows (that really open) and great views of the city streets and skyline. It is tastefully furnished in subdued tones, complete with a desk and walk-in closet. The bed and bath linens are luxuriously thick and are fresh and clean each day. Amenities match or exceed those of any major chain hotel. In addition, there is complimentary wireless internet and a large keyed safe in the closet that easily secured my laptop computer and other belongings if I so chose. Hotel staff are readily prepared to offer suggestions for just about anywhere you might want or need to go in the city - from restaurants to nail salons! Each suggestion is followed with details regarding the establishment, many times with the name of a person who can help you when you arrive. Never was I offered a telephone book to search on my own. A town car was arranged for my transportation back to airport (at the same cost as a local cab ride). The location of the King George is nearly in the heart of Union Square and central to many attractions. Excellent restaurants as well as fast-food is available within a block in all directions. I would highly recommend the Santorini Restaurant for lunch or dinner.A note to cigarette smokers: the King George has smoking rooms available. If you are looking for the stark environment of a major chain hotel, then this is not the place to stay. But if, like me, you appreciate the charm and unique flavor of San Francisco I would highly recommend this hotel and its warm and welcoming staff. I will be returning to visit again soon.	
