Jun 26 2008 	The comfiest bed in the world!	Stayed 19-25 June 2008 and can honestly say that this is one of the best city hotels I've ever stayed in. The staff on reception were friendly and welcoming on arrival despite our late check-in. Our room was perfect. Although it didn't have the nicest of views (over a low roof and the side of the next building) it was utterly peaceful and quiet. Yes, there was a little noise from other residents in the corridor, but we heard very little from the guests in the rooms on either side.The room itself was great, we had temperatures ranging from 103 on one day to 53 the next and the heating and overhead fan were more than enough to keep the room at a comfortable temperature. The bed was the most amazingly comfy bed we've ever slept in, just what we needed after a long day hiking up the San Francisco streets!Amenity wise the room had everything you could need - a safe, an ironing board &amp; iron, coffee &amp; tea facilities, a hair dryer and even a candy jar!Our room was compact but perfectly comfortable and while the bathroom is small it's not too small and we found it easy enough to manouvre about. The sheets, towels and room in general were clean and fresh as was the rest of the hotel.Breakfast at the hotel is a typical continental breakfast. Croissant, muffins, cereals, yoghurts, fruit &amp; coffee/tea all for $7.95. There are diners either side of the hotel offering great American breakfasts too, but we found the hotel breakfast suited us better.We used the hotel bar too and while quiet, was comfortable, well priced and the staff were friendly there.The location of the hotel (2 mins from Union Square &amp; 5 mins from Powel Street Cable, Bart &amp; Muni) is second to none. The hotel is surrounded by restaurants, shops and any other amenity you could need and is perfectly placed as a base for viewing the rest of the city.All in all the King George really helped make our stay in San Francisco fantastic and I'd recommend it to anyone.Just one last thing - we transferred at JFK New York in both directions and had delays of at least an hour and in some cases 2(which caused us a bit of a panic on the way to SF although we still made it due to the efficiency of the Delta airline transfer ground staff) if you're going this way make sure you leave at least 3 hrs for transfers as delays at JFK seem to be a regular thing.	
