Sep 20 2007 	Fun and Friendly	The King George is ideally located just two blocks from Union square. The walk to the hotel from the Powell Bart station was only five minutes. Our room was on the first floor away from the street, so our room was very quiet. The room size was larger than expected after reading earlier reviews. Everything was neat and tidy and nicely decorated. We have no complaints at all about the hotel. The staff are extremely friendly. We enjoyed a few drinks at happy hour while the bartender entertained us with his witty sense of humour. The continental breakfast was ok but we enjoyed the dinners located next door to the hotel. The location is perfect and safe, however, areas west of the hotel are a little sketchy. Most of the tourist areas are north or east. The cable car line is two blocks away on Powell. We did not take a taxi once our entire stay in SFO. The hotel is recommended and we would definately stay here again. The value of this hotel cannot be beat.	
Sep 14 2007 	King George Hotel: Modest digs GREAT location	On a whim, my husband and I decided to visit San Francisco. We knew that we wanted to stay in a nice area of town, but that we didn't want to spend a lot of money. Enter the King George Hotel (&quot;KGH&quot;).ABOUT THE PROPERTYIf you weren't specifically looking for it, you might miss the entrance. KGH faces Mason Street, snuggled between (what appeared to be) two 50's era diners (we didn't try them out, but I'm willing to bet at least one of those diners made a pretty mean chocolate milkshake). If there's one thing you need to know about KGH, it's this: the rooms are incredibly small, like the size of my bedroom, and that INCLUDES the closet and bathroom. I'd guesstimate the average room size (with one bed -- obviously, rooms with double beds would have to be larger) to be about 14'x14'. Also, there aren't many blankets on the beds, which can be problematic if you're cold-natured, like me. So be sure to pack a pair of wool socks.If there's another thing you need to know about KGH, it's this: the room rates are incredibly low, like half of what you'd pay at any other hotel in the area. Unless you're staying at the W, and then you can expect to pay roughly 1/3 of the going rate, which means you'll be able to afford to try all those alleyway restaurants. (And believe me, they're well worth it.)LOCATION, LOCATION, LOCATIONKGH is in the middle of it all: Union Square, Chinatown, Nob Hill, Downtown/Financial District, Fisherman's Wharf, the Mission, Haight-Ashbury (note: &quot;Haight&quot; is pronounced &quot;Hate&quot;), etc. KGH is about three blocks from Market Street, where you can catch nearly any bus to any of the above-named locations (and more!) or take the BART to an outlying area. It is just a block or two from tons of shopping at Union Square. It is in a safe neighborhood. Beware of homeless people though, they are all over the city and may accost you for money if you appear to friendly. Try to look gruff, if you can manage. RANDOM DETAILS ABOUT THE PROPERTYSTAFF: Ultra-friendly, ultra-helpful. Had no qualms about allowing us a late checkout (two hours late), and stowed our bags in a locked room so that we could go out for the day after checkout but before our late flight left.ELEVATOR: There is one very small, very old elevator. It can comfortably fit two people with luggage. It can snugly fit two people with luggage and two people without luggage or six people, all without luggage. Because the KGH is in such an old building, I think this type of elevator must be customary.ROOM WINDOWS: The room windows are fun because you can actually open them, all the way, and there is no screen. I don't suggest jumping. We were on the sixth floor and had a city view, which was fun because we became enchanted with the city-ness of it all. The sounds from the streets and smells from the local restaurants wafted through our room and enticed our curiosity to explore. ROOM SIZE: Rooms are small and clean. I don't suggest that you attempt fitting more than two people in a room (unless, again, you get a larger-than-standard-size room). You will LITERALLY be climbing on top of each other. Unless you're into that sort of thing.RESTROOMS: The lobby restrooms are nice, very well lit and private with full doors. I can't speak for ALL the private bathrooms, but ours was passable. It was clean, but I did have to leave a maintenance request to fix the toilet. Contrary to its purpose, the toilet did not like to flush.SPIRAL STAIRCASE: There is a very tall, very narrow spiral staircase that runs from the basement, through the lobby, to every floor of the building. Walk it once, just to say you did. Try not to get dizzy.INTERNET CONNECTION: Wi-fi is free in the hotel, which is a bonus. Sometimes it is finicky from the rooms, but keep trying. You can ALWAYS access it from the lobby.CONTINENTAL BREAKFAST: Is not free, which is fine, since there are so many awesome eateries in San Francisco anyway.WHAT TO DO IN SAN FRANCISCOThis is certainly not all-inclusive, and what you choose to do should highly depend on how much time you have and what you enjoy doing. Obviously. San Francisco is rich in culture and there is ALWAYS something going on. Things I suggest:* SELF-GUIDED DRIVING TOUR- Rent a car (conveniently, there is a Hertz car rental across the street from KGH) and drive to (a) Sausalito and (b) John Muir Woods. Be sure to stop at Stinson Beach, and take a day drive along Highway 1. Preferably in a convertible, if weather allows, or at least with a sunroof and the windows down.* CLIFF HOUSE RESTAURANT - a historical area that has been turned into an upscale restaurant. We ate in the bistro. There isn't a bad seat in the house. We were seated right next to a window that served as a beach overlook. The Cliff House is located on the West coast of San Francisco, right on the Pacific Ocean. Expect to spend around $20 per person, plus tip.* FISHERMAN'S WHARF - Very touristy, but it's kind of a place you must visit. Visit one of the first days you're in town, and the rest of the trip will be up-hill. Go hungry and get clam chowder in a bread bowl. Delicious! Wander around, maybe catch a tour to Alcatraz (or just stand and stare at it from the wharf). If you're lucky you'll have chosen a time to visit while the seals are sunning themselves on the docks. Hundreds of them - just follow the barking noise until you find them.* CHINATOWN - I love, love, love Chinatown. But that may be because I'm infatuated with Asian cultures. Move off the beaten path (tourist mecca of Grant Street, home of the three-dollar I VISITED ALCATRAZ t-shirts, cheaply embroidered coin purses and gaudy gold buddhas) and go up any of the side streets (Kearny or Stockton, for example) or tiny alleyways. THAT is where you'll find the real Chinatown. * MISSION or HAIGHT-ASHBURY - Take a bus to the Mission or Haight-Ashbury. There's a ton of nightlife that will beckon you. My favorite was Cha Cha Cha on Haight, a tapas restaurant with Sangria by the pitcher (or the glass, if you're feeling puny) and liquor-infused fruit that might knock you over after just one nibble. The music is loud and the wait is long, but the atmosphere is totally worth it. The food is pretty good, too. Be sure to order the Warm Spinach Salad. You'll fight your tablemates to lick the plate.All-in-all, KGH is a central location with great prices. I would stay there again. And San Francisco? Well, SF is a paradise for young, old, gay, straight, male, female. If you don't fall in love with the city by the time you leave, it's possible that you have no soul.	
